The Neutrino Factory was first proposed in the 1990s as an accelerator-based infrastructure for producing a neutrino beam of sufficiently high intensity for leptonic CP-violation discovery and measurement. In a Neutrino Factory, a very high-power proton accelerator is used to produce a high-intensity pion flux from which, by the decay of the pions, a high-intensity muon beam is derived. This muon beam is subsequently cooled, accelerated, and led into a racetrack storage ring, where the muons decay and produce a beam composed of equal amounts of νμ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\nu _\mu$$\end{document} and νe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\nu _{\mathrm{e}}$$\end{document}. Building a Neutrino Factory will be a very challenging task, in particular because of the required cooling and acceleration of the very short-lived muons.

