An independent measurement of the incident neutrino flux can be achieved by observing elastic scattering of neutrinos on atomic electrons in the water. This process yields a free electron in the final state, and is well suited for a flux measurement, because its cross-section can be calculated theoretically with high precision. This cross-section is, however, three-to-four orders of magnitude smaller than that of neutrino-nucleus scattering, so events produced with this process must be efficiently selected in a large sample of νe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
