				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1\times 1\times {1}\,{\text {cm}}^{3}$$\end{document} each, read out by a three-dimensional pattern of wave-length-shifting optical fibres (see Fig. 158). MPPC (Multi-Pixel Photon Counters, equivalent to SiPMs) are connected at each end of the optical fibres. Our baseline is to use ∼106\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim 10^6$$\end{document} cubes, forming a rectangular cuboid with dimensions 1.4×1.4×0.5m3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1.4\times 1.4\times 0.5\,{\text {m}}^{3}$$\end{document}. The thickness of 0.5 m along the neutrino beam is chosen to let more charged leptons penetrate into the water Cherenkov detector tank, thus allow for combined event analysis. A magnetic field of up to 1 T oriented perpendicular to the beam is applied in the tracker by a dipole magnet (see Fig. 135).Fig. 158
